    • preorderRecursive

      public void preorderRecursive(BinaryTreeNode<Integer> root)
      root, left subtree, right subtree. Note that a pre-order traversal gives the Euler tour (minus reversed edges) for this tree when Euler start node is the root. 
             e.g.
                            7
                3                        11
           1         5              9         13
        0   2     4   6           8   10    12

     visits: 7, 3, 1, 0, 2,5,4,6,11,9,8,10,13,12
      Parameters:
      root - root of tree

    • reverseLevelOrderIterative

      public void reverseLevelOrderIterative(BinaryTreeNode<Integer> node)
      get the reverse level-order traversal of tree node. implemented as post-order traversal but using a queue for the first stack: adapted from https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/inorder-tree-traversal-without-recursion/?ref=gcse 
             e.g.
                            7
                3                        11
           1         5              9         13
        0   2     4   6           8   10    12

     visits: 12, 10, 8, 6, 4, 2, 0, 13, 9, 5, 1, 11, 3, 7
      Parameters:
      node -

    • getReverseLevelOrderIterative2

      public DoublyLinkedList<NAryTreeNode> getReverseLevelOrderIterative2(NAryTreeNode node)
      given a tree represented by node, return a doubly-linked list of nodes visited in a reverse level-order traversal.
      Parameters:
      node - the tree to be traversed from bottom up to this node using reverse level-order traversal. NOTE that any next and prev links in the tree are overwritten by the DoublyLinkedList, so if those need to be preserved, give this method node.copyTree() instead.
      Returns:
      a double-linked list of nodes in reverse level order traversal.

    • predeccesor

      public BinaryTreeNode<Integer> predeccesor(BinaryTreeNode<Integer> node)
      find the predeccesor node to node in a binary search tree. 
           following CLRS chap 12
     ( Cormen, Leiserson, Rivest, and Stein "Introduction to Algorithms")

     e.g.
     the predecessor of 5 is 4.
     if 4 were null, the predecessor of 5 is 3.
                            7
                3                        11
           1         5              9         13
        0   2     4   6           8   10    12

      Returns:
